President Obama has announced his intent to nominate Michael S. Owen as Ambassador to the Republic of Sierra Leone. Owen is a career member of the Senior Foreign Service and currently serves as Acting Deputy Assistant Secretary in the Bureau of South and Central Asian Affairs. He has previously served in various positions in India, Tanzania, Ghana, Sri Lanka, Pakistan, Mauritania, and Ireland. Owen holds a B.S. in Civil Engineering and Economics from Rice University and a Masters in Public Affairs from Princeton University.

President Obama also announced his intent to appoint several individuals to serve as members on the American Battle Monuments Commission. These individuals include Darrell Dorgan, who has served as the Executive Director of the North Dakota Cowboy Hall of Fame; John L. Estrada, a retired Sergeant Major of the United States Marine Corps; Evelyn Foote, a retired Brigadier General of the United States Army; Rolland Kidder, a Vietnam War veteran and Director of Friends of the National World War Memorial; Richard L. Klass, a retired Air Force Colonel and president of the Veterans Alliance for Security and Democracy; Merrill A. McPeak, a retired General of the U.S. Air Force and chairman of Ethicspoint; Ambassador Constance Morella, a former Congresswoman and Ambassador to the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development; and Maura C. Sullivan, a former Marine Captain who served in Iraq and now works for PepsiCo.